ohn Roberts]]\n* [[Thomas Roberts (news anchor)|Thomas Roberts]] \n* [[Susan Roesgen]]\n* [[Dan Ronan]]\n* [[Susan Rook]]\n* [[Lynne Russell]]\n* [[Brent Sadler]]\n* [[Zoraida Sambolin]]\n* [[Rick Sanchez (journalist)|Rick Sanchez]]\n* [[Andreas van der Schaaf]]\n* [[Bill Schneider (journalist)|Bill Schneider]]\n* [[Isha Sesay]] \n* [[Frank Sesno]]\n* [[Bella Shaw]]\n* [[Bernard Shaw (journalist)|Bernard Shaw]] (retired)\n* [[Mark Shields]]\n* [[Daniel Schorr]] (deceased)\n* [[Kate Snow]] \n* [[Tony Snow]] (deceased)\n* [[Linden Soles]]\n* [[Martin Soong]]\n* [[Flip Spiceland]]\n* [[Eliot Spitzer]]\n* [[Linda Stouffer]]\n* [[Kathleen_Sullivan_(journalist)|Kathleen Sullivan]]\n* [[Fionnuala Sweeney]]\n* [[Lisa Sylvester]] \n* [[Abbi Tatton]]\n* [[Felicia Taylor]] \n* [[Jonathan Tasini]]\n* [[Owen Thomas (journalist)|Owen Thomas]]\n* [[Andrea Thompson]]\n* [[Mary Tillotson]]\n* [[Toria Tolley]]\n* [[Alphonso Van Marsh]]\n* [[Greta Van Susteren]] \n* [[Stuart Varney]] \n* [[Lyn Vaughn]]\n* [[Luis Carlos V\u00e9lez]]\n* [[Amelyn Veloso]] (deceased)\n* [[Ali Velshi]] \n* [[Alessio Vinci]]\n* [[Valerie Voss]]\n* [[David Walker (journalist)|Dave Walker]] (retired)\n* [[Mark S. Walton]] \n* [[Michael Ware]]\n* [[Margaret Warner]] \n* [[Lou Waters]] (retired)\n* [[Bernard Watson]]\n* [[Bob Weaver (weatherman)|Bob Weaver]] (deceased)\n* [[Rafer Weigel]]\n* [[Ralph Wenge]]\n* [[Harris Whitbeck]]\n* [[Liz Wickersham]]\n* [[Mary Alice Williams]]\n* [[Beverly Williams]] \n* [[Gerri Willis]] \n* [[Reynolds Wolf]] \n* [[Jack Womack]]\n* [[Judy Woodruff]] \n* [[Van Earl Wright]]\n* [[Jessica Yellin]] \n* [[Paula Zahn]]\n* [[John Zarrella]]\n* [[Charles Zewe]]\n* [[Bill Zimmerman]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CNN Anchors}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of television presenters|CNN anchors]]\n[[Category:CNN people| ]]\n", "name_user": "Mall8o", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edit name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_CNN_personnel"}
{"title_page": "Riverside Stadium (Washington, D.C.)", "text_new": "{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Riverside Stadium\n| nickname          =  \n| image             =  \n| image_size        =  \n| caption           =  \n| fullname          = Riverside Stadium\n| location          = [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|38.8948340|-77.0555328|region:US_type:landmark|display=it}} <ref>GNIS Datat Riverside Stadium (historical) https://geonames.usgs.gov/apex/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:529603</ref>\n| built             =  \n| opened            = 1938\n| renovated         =\n| closed            = 1952\n| demolished        =\n| owner             =  \n| operator          = L. E. and S. G. Leoffler  \n| surface           =  \n| construction_cost = \n| architect         =\n| former_names      =\n| tenants           = \n| seating_capacity  = \n| dimensions        = \n|}}\n\n'''Riverside Stadium''' was a multi-purpose [[sports arena]] with a [[roller rink]] in [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]].\n\n== History ==\nRiverside Stadium was opened to the public in 1938. It was demolished to make way for the construction of the larger landmark, the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|National Cultural Center]]. The new stadium was renamed in 1964 as the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] following the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]].\n\nIn the early 1940s, Riverside Stadium played host to several ''\"ice carnivals\"'' and was considered to be an important venue to showcase competitive skating skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.weta.org/boundarystones/2016/01/05/ice-carnival-tidal-basin|title=Ice Carnival at the Tidal Basin|last=WETA|website=Boundary Stones: WETA's Washington DC History Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== List of sporting events held in the stadium (1938-1952) ===\n\n* Eastern Regional Championships of the Roller Skating Rinks of the United States, May 30-June 1, 1948.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dfUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69&dq=riverside+stadium+washington+dc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq16SI4IzpAhXgxzgGHQLVCJgQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=riverside%20stadium%20washington%20dc&f=false|title=D.C. Skaters Big Winners in Pitt's RSROA Regional|date=1948-06-19|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)]]|year=1948|isbn=|location=|pages=69|language=en}}</ref>\n*Roller Skating Rink's Operators Association (RSROA) American Championship, July 11-16, 1949.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Amateur Roller Skating Championship of the Roller Skating Rink's Operators Association (RSROA), July 11-16, 1949.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Jw4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT61&lpg=PT61&dq=riverside+stadium+roller+skating&source=bl&ots=y9DwWZbjZg&sig=ACfU3U17UQL8_QDQwZtTl2cPB6gMPkt2ZQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj62KnQ_ozpAhVUwTgGHQwnCesQ6AEwCHoECFQQAQ#v=onepage&q=riverside%20stadium%20roller%20skating&f=false|title=Billboard|date=1949-07-30|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== List of non-sporting events held in the stadium (1938-1952) ===\n\n* Democraic Forum conducted by women's division of the [[Democratic National Committee]], on the evening of May 3, 1940.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Congress|first=United States|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Yp7I8KFUCy8C&pg=PA2691&lpg=PA2691&dq=Democratic+Forum+1940+Riverside+Stadium&source=bl&ots=Fnh0MkYf_z&sig=ACfU3U3FkNqKLZpmSdWdejG6YM_m4AEn0w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjg2IWf5YzpAhUcyzgGHTVDBiIQ6AEwAHoECBEQAQ#v=onepage&q=Democratic%20Forum%201940%20Riverside%20Stadium&f=false|title=Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the ... Congress|date=1940|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1940|isbn=|series=15|volume=86|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|pages=2691|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Other usage ===\n\n* It has been stated in various [[United States Supreme Court]]'s documents that the stadium was used by [[Central Intelligence Agency]] between 1961 to 1963.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Claims|first=United States Court of|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=gOLzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA433&lpg=PA433&dq=riverside+stadium+demolished+washington+dc&source=bl&ots=5sFFKZ5Tgk&sig=ACfU3U3Lmelt3BcIYLo2B_HDMVLozIePuQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwie0rXO4ozpAhXK4jgGHXehB18Q6AEwF3oECC0QAQ#v=onepage&q=riverside%20stadium&f=false|title=Cases Decided in the United States Court of Claims ... with Report of Decisions of the Supreme Court in Court of Claims Cases|last2=Bernhardt|first2=Audrey|date=1973|publisher=The Court|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authoritycontrol}}\n\n[[Category:Destroyed_landmarks_in_Washington,_D.C.]]\n[[Category:Demolished_buildings_and_structures_in_Washington,_D.C.]]\n[[Category:Defunct_sports_venues_in_Washington,_D.C.]]\n[[Category:Demolished_sports_venues_in_the_United_States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Riverside Stadium\n| nickname          =  \n| image             =  \n| image_size        =  \n| caption           =  \n| fullname          = Riverside Stadium\n| location          = [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|38.8948340|-77.0555328|region:US_type:landmark|display=it}}\n| built             =  \n| opened            = 1938\n| renovated         =\n| closed            = 1952\n| demolished        =\n| owner             =  \n| operator          = L. E. and S. G. Leoffler  \n| surface           =  \n| construction_cost = \n| architect         =\n| former_names      =\n| tenants           = \n| seating_capacity  = \n| dimensions        = \n|}}\n\n'''Riverside Stadium''' was a multi-purpose [[sports arena]] with a [[roller rink]] in [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]].\n\n== History ==\nRiverside Stadium was opened to the public in 1938. It was demolished to make way for the construction of the larger landmark, the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|National Cultural Center]]. The new stadium was renamed in 1964 as the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] following the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]].\n\nIn the early 1940s, Riverside Stadium played host to several ''\"ice carnivals\"'' and was considered to be an important venue to showcase competitive skating skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.weta.org/boundarystones/2016/01/05/ice-carnival-tidal-basin|title=Ice Carnival at the Tidal Basin|last=WETA|website=Boundary Stones: WETA's Washington DC History Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== List of sporting events held in the stadium (1938-1952) ===\n\n* Eastern Regional Championships of the Roller Skating Rinks of the United States, May 30-June 1, 1948.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dfUDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69&dq=riverside+stadium+washington+dc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq16SI4IzpAhXgxzgGHQLVCJgQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=riverside%20stadium%20washington%20dc&f=false|title=D.C. Skaters Big Winners in Pitt's RSROA Regional|date=1948-06-19|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)]]|year=1948|isbn=|location=|pages=69|language=en}}</ref>\n*Roller Skating Rink's Operators Association (RSROA) American Championship, July 11-16, 1949.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*Amateur Roller Skating Championship of the Roller Skating Rink's Operators Association (RSROA), July 11-16, 1949.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Jw4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT61&lpg=PT61&dq=riverside+stadium+roller+skating&source=bl&ots=y9DwWZbjZg&sig=ACfU3U17UQL8_QDQwZtTl2cPB6gMPkt2ZQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj62KnQ_ozpAhVUwTgGHQwnCesQ6AEwCHoECFQQAQ#v=onepage&q=riverside%20stadium%20roller%20skating&f=false|title=Billboard|date=1949-07-30|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== List of non-sporting events held in the stadium (1938-1952) ===\n\n* Democraic Forum conducted by women's division of the [[Democratic National Committee]], on the evening of May 3, 1940.<ref>{{Cite book|las